= The Anti-Corruption Campaign

The Soviet anti-corruption campaign was launched in 1982 under then-General Secretary
Yuri Andropov, whose rise to power coincided with the identification of corruption as one of the central
threats to the Soviet political system. Among the campaign’s leading causes was a realization that
increased discipline at all levels of Soviet society could be an asset both towards economic resurgence as
well as popular support. By increasing the penalties of corruption at all levels of government, Andropov’s
tenure saw the removal of some officials, and the public arrests of others. Following Andropov,
Konstantin Chernenko’s reign saw a public commitment to the cause, albeit with some partiality towards
Chernenko’s closest officials.

As expected, the Kremlin’s stance on corruption has been popular with the public. The mobilisation of the
KGB against corrupt officials has increased public trust in the government, with many seeing the
increased discipline as a means of increasing the Politburo’s capacity to handle problems.

We have options with regards to this policy. It is widely expected that, as an understudy of Andropov,
General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev will not only assume Andropov’s stance on corruption, but
reinvigorate it. In line with the Politburo’s expectation that Gorbachev will continue Andropov’s reforms
with a certain zeal, any reservations on the anti-corruption campaign would be surprising.

